description:
In inbox.rs verify_and_fetch_actor (lines 405-417), the Date header freshness check uses:

    if let Ok(date_str) = date_val.to_str() {
        if let Ok(parsed) = chrono::DateTime::parse_from_rfc2822(date_str) {
            // enforce 5-minute window
        }
    }

If the Date header value contains non-ASCII bytes (to_str() fails) or is not valid RFC 2822 (parse fails), the freshness check is silently skipped. The Date header is still present and signed (required by line 433-435), so the signature is still verified — but the anti-replay window is not enforced.

A malicious server can sign a request with a syntactically-valid-for-signature but unparseable Date (e.g. 'Thu, 99 Xxx 2099 00:00:00 GMT') and the request will pass signature verification with no time bound — the signed payload can be replayed indefinitely (subject to key rotation).

Impact: infinite signature replay window when Date is malformed.

Fix: return Err if either to_str() or parse_from_rfc2822() fails:

    let date_str = date_val.to_str().map_err(|_| AppError::unauthorized('unparseable Date'))?;
    let parsed = chrono::DateTime::parse_from_rfc2822(date_str)
        .map_err(|_| AppError::unauthorized('malformed Date header'))?;
